ST. JOHN CHRYSOSTOM'S HOMILY 3 ON GENESIS (UNABRIDGED AUDIOBOOK SCRIPT)

================================================================================

Reading the Holy Scriptures is very much like discovering a hidden treasure. 
Just as someone who secures even a tiny fragment from a gold vault immediately 
finds themselves much wealthier, the exact same rule applies to the divine 
Scriptures. Even within a brief, isolated phrase, you can discover an immense 
depth of meaning and an inexhaustible spiritual fortune. 

But the words of Scripture are not merely a treasure chest; they are also like 
a vibrant, everlasting fountain whose waters never stop flowing. We all witnessed 
this truth firsthand yesterday by our own experience. When we opened the very 
first pages of the book of Creation to examine the phrase, "In the beginning 
God made heaven and earth" (Genesis 1:1), we spent our entire allocated teaching 
time unpacking just those few words—and even then, we could not exhaust their 
full depth. The abundance of this treasure is simply too vast, and the streams of 
this spiritual fountain flow too generously.

Do not be surprised that this happens to us. Generation after generation of 
believers before us have drawn from these waters according to their own strength, 
and those who come after us will try to do the exact same thing. Yet, no one 
will ever be able to drain this fountain dry. Instead, the streams keep flowing, 
the waters continue to rise, and the riverbeds expand. This is the unique nature 
of spiritual rivers: the more eagerly and deeply a person approaches them with 
desire, the more the spiritual grace of the Holy Spirit overflows. 

This is precisely why Christ said, "If anyone thirsts, let him come to Me and drink. 
He who believes in Me, as the Scripture has said, out of his heart will flow rivers 
of living water" (John 7:37–38). He used these words to demonstrate the boundless, 
overflowing nature of these divine streams. Therefore, since this is the true 
nature of spiritual waters, let us all bring the vessels of our minds to this 
fountain and draw from them freely, so that we may return home filled and transformed.

When the grace of the Holy Spirit sees a soul burning with spiritual desire and 
a mind that is fully awake and watchful, it distributes its gifts even more 
richly. So let us intentionally pull ourselves away from worldly anxieties, and 
let us cut off the everyday worries that choke our thoughts like thorns (cf. Matthew 13:22). 
Let us turn our entire focus toward spiritual desire, so that by gaining a great 
practical benefit here and receiving something noble and good, we may leave this 
place strengthened.

To ensure that this teaching remains completely clear, let us briefly remind your 
love of what was discussed yesterday, so that today’s insights may be seamlessly 
joined to yesterday’s, forming one unbroken body of truth. Yesterday, as you 
remember, we showed how the blessed Moses, while explaining the creation of the 
visible world, stated, "In the beginning God made heaven and earth" (Genesis 1:1). 
And he immediately added, "The earth was invisible and without form" (Genesis 1:2). 
We also explained the underlying reasons why God first brought the earth forth 
without shape and without order, and I believe you remember those explanations well.

Now it is necessary to move forward in the text. After stating that "the earth 
was invisible and without form," Scripture carefully details exactly why this 
was the case, explaining that "darkness was over the face of the deep, and the 
Spirit of God was moving over the waters" (Genesis 1:2). 

Notice the careful restraint of the blessed prophet. He does not explain every 
minor detail of creation. After naming the primary components, heaven and earth, 
he leaves other elements unspoken. For instance, although he has not yet explicitly 
described the creation of the waters, he already notes that "darkness was over the 
deep, and the Spirit of God was moving over the waters" (Genesis 1:2). This dark, 
abyssal ocean completely covered the face of the earth. From this sequence, we learn 
that everything visible was once submerged under water and shrouded in darkness, 
and that it required the wisdom of the supreme Creator to remove this primeval 
disorder and bring about structure and beauty.

What does it mean, then, when Scripture states that "the Spirit of God was moving 
over the waters" (Genesis 1:2)? It does not mean that the water possessed an 
independent life of its own. Instead, it demonstrates that God was already actively 
at work, preparing creation by His power and care. What is completely motionless 
is useless, but what is moved and directed by God becomes ready to receive His 
creative command. Scripture records this fact ahead of time because it will 
later tell us that living creatures were brought forth directly from these waters 
by God’s spoken command (cf. Genesis 1:20).

Because everything was initially covered in raw disorder, God, the perfect craftsman, 
issued His decree, and that chaos was instantly driven away. Then the great, 
unimagined beauty of visible light appeared, and the darkness fled. As it is written, 
"And God said, 'Let there be light,' and there was light" (Genesis 1:3). He spoke—and 
it instantly happened. He commanded—and the darkness retreated. 

Do you see the incredible, unmatched power of His word? Yet, despite this clarity, 
some people who are blinded by philosophical error ignore the structural order of 
Scripture and claim that raw matter must have existed before creation. What could 
possibly be more foolish than this assertion? Scripture clearly and repeatedly states 
that God made all things from absolute nothingness. Is God a mere human artisan, 
that He would require pre-existing materials before He could display His craft? 
He is God, who creates the entire universe by His spoken word alone.

The text continues: "And God separated the light from the darkness" (Genesis 1:4). 
This means He assigned each element its proper domain and established the precise, 
right time for each to operate. Then He gave them their official names: "God called 
the light Day, and the darkness He called Night" (Genesis 1:5). 

Do you see the perfect order and the wondrous creation accomplished by God’s command 
alone? God taught humanity gently, using simple, accessible concepts, because we 
were not yet mature enough to comprehend higher, unmediated spiritual teaching. 
For this reason, the Holy Spirit deliberately spoke through the prophet's tongue 
in a way that accommodated human weakness. 

So let us receive the teaching of Scripture with deep gratitude. Let us run 
eagerly toward the light and live our lives as children of the day (cf. Romans 13:12–13). 
To Him be glory, with the Father and the Holy Spirit, now and forever, and 
unto the endless ages of ages. Amen.
